\f1\fs24 \cf0 Note the alternative syntax for playing a Routine. aClock.play(aRoutine) and aRoutine.play(aClock) are functionally equivalent. The two make different things more or less convienent, like sending messages to the 
\f0\b Routine
\f1\b0  or 
\f0\b Clock
\f1\b0 . (See the 
\f0\b play
\f1\b0  helpfile for a more detailed discussion.) For instance:\
\
	
\f2\fs18 (\
	\cf2 // this, that and the other\cf0 \
	r = \cf3 Routine\cf0 .new(\{\cf3 var\cf0  i = 0; \{ (\cf4 "this: "\cf0  ++ i).postln; i = i + 1; 1.yield; \}.loop \});\
	q = \cf3 Routine\cf0 .new(\{\cf3 var\cf0  i = 0; \{ (\cf4 "that: "\cf0  ++ i).postln; i = i + 1; 1.yield; \}.loop \}); \cf2 \
	\cf0 t = \cf3 Routine\cf0 .new(\{\cf3 var\cf0  i = 0; \{ (\cf4 "the other: "\cf0  ++ i).postln; i = i + 1; 1.yield; \}.loop \});\
	)\
	\
	\cf3 SystemClock\cf0 .play(r); 	\cf2 // start this\cf0 \
	\cf3 SystemClock\cf0 .play(q); 	\cf2 // start that\
	\cf3 SystemClock\cf0 .play(t); 	\cf2 // start the other\cf0 \
	\
	r.stop; 				\cf2 // stop this but not that or the other\cf0 \
	q.reset;				\cf2 // reset that while playing\
	\cf0 \
	c = \cf3 TempoClock\cf0 .new;	\cf2 // make a TempoClock\cf0 \
	r.reset;				\cf2 // have to reset this because it's stopped\cf0 \
	c.play(r);			\cf2 // play this in the new clock; starts from the beginning\cf0 \
	c.tempo = 16;			\cf2 // increase the tempo of this\
	\cf0 \
	\cf3 SystemClock\cf0 .clear; 	\cf2 // clear EVERYTHING scheduled in the SystemClock; so that and the other \
						// but not this\
						\cf0 \
	c.clear;				\cf2 // clear everything scheduled in c, i.e. this\cf0 \
	c.play(r);			\cf2 // since it wasn't stopped, we don't have to reset this\
						// and it picks up where it left off\
						\cf0 \
	c.stop				\cf2 // stop c, destroy its scheduler, and release its OS thread
